.TH PWLDAPD 8 "March 2026" "pwldapd" "System Administration"
.
.SH NAME
pwldapd \- LDAP daemon backed by the local POSIX user and group database
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B pwldapd
.RB [ \-c
.IR file ]
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B pwldapd
is a read-only LDAP server (RFC\ 4510) that exposes the local POSIX user
and group database over the LDAP protocol.
It reads accounts through the system's name-service switch (NSS) layer
and presents them as a standard
.BR posixAccount / inetOrgPerson
and
.B posixGroup
directory tree.
Bind requests are authenticated via PAM.
Anonymous binds are accepted by default; the
.B require_bind
configuration option can restrict searches to specific accounts (see
.BR "BIND REQUIREMENT" ).
.PP
The daemon is intended for use on a single host where LDAP-aware
applications\(emsuch as SSH, sudo, or web servers\(emneed to look up
local accounts without requiring a separate directory service.
It does not persist any state and does not support write operations.
.
.SS Directory structure
The served tree is rooted at the base DN (see
.BR \-\-base\-dn )
and has the following layout:
.PP
.RS
.nf
dc=host,dc=example,dc=com
\(lc\(em ou=people
\(lc   \(lc\(em uid=alice,...
\(lc   \(aq\(em uid=bob,...
\(aq\(em ou=groups
    \(lc\(em cn=staff,...
    \(aq\(em cn=wheel,...
.fi
.RE
.PP
Each
.B uid=\c
\fIname\fR
entry under
.B ou=people
carries the following attributes:
.BR objectClass " (top, posixAccount, inetOrgPerson),"
.BR uid ,
.BR cn ,
.BR sn ,
.BR uidNumber ,
.BR gidNumber ,
.BR homeDirectory ,
.BR loginShell ,
.BR gecos .
The
.BR givenName ,
.BR roomNumber ,
.BR telephoneNumber ,
and
.B homePhone
attributes are also populated when the corresponding GECOS fields
are non-empty (see
.BR "GECOS PARSING" ).
Additional attributes may be defined in the configuration file (see
.BR "USER ATTRIBUTES" ).
.PP
Each
.B cn=\c
\fIname\fR
entry under
.B ou=groups
carries:
.BR objectClass " (top, posixGroup),"
.BR cn ,
.BR gidNumber ,
.BR memberUid .
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-c " file" ", \-\-config=" file
Path to a TOML configuration file.
See
.B CONFIGURATION FILE
for the file format and
.B USER ATTRIBUTES
for the attribute extension syntax.
When this option is omitted,
.B pwldapd
looks for
.B /etc/pwldapd.toml
and loads it if present.
If neither an explicit path nor the default file is found,
.B pwldapd
starts with built-in defaults: listening on
.BR 127.0.0.1:389 ,
the base DN derived from the system hostname, and all UIDs and GIDs served.
.
.SH CONFIGURATION FILE
.B pwldapd
accepts a TOML configuration file specified with
.BR \-\-config .
If the flag is omitted,
.B /etc/pwldapd.toml
is loaded automatically when present.
.PP
All fields are optional.
Unknown fields are rejected at startup so that typos are caught immediately
rather than silently ignored.
.PP
An annotated example covering every option:
.PP
.RS
.nf
include      = ["/etc/pwldapd.d/*.conf"]
listen       = ["127.0.0.1:389"]
tls_listen   = ["[::]:636"]
unix_listen  = ["/run/pwldapd/ldap.sock"]
base_dn      = "dc=example,dc=com"
uid_ranges   = ["1000\-65535"]
gid_ranges   = ["1000\-65535"]
tls_cert     = "/etc/ssl/certs/ldap.pem"
tls_key      = "/etc/ssl/private/ldap.key"
log_level    = "info"
require_bind = ["svcaccount"]

[user_attributes]
mail       = "{uid}@example.com"
department = "Engineering"

[user_overrides.alice]
mail       = "alice@external.com"
department = "Platform Engineering"
.fi
.RE
.PP
The
.B include
field takes a list of glob patterns.
Each matching file is loaded and merged before the values in the main file;
the main file always takes precedence.
Included files may not themselves contain
.B include
directives.
.PP
Each entry in
.B uid_ranges
and
.B gid_ranges
is either a single number
.RI ( N )
or an inclusive range
.RI ( N\-M ).
.PP
If a port is omitted from a
.B listen
address,
.B :389
is appended automatically.
For
.BR tls_listen ,
the default port is
.BR :636 .
To suppress the built-in default of
.BR 127.0.0.1:389 ,
set
.B listen
to an empty list:
.PP
.RS
.nf
listen = []
.fi
.RE
.PP
The
.B [user_attributes]
and
.B [user_overrides]
sections are described in
.BR "USER ATTRIBUTES" .
.
.SH USER ATTRIBUTES
The
.B [user_attributes]
section of the configuration file defines extra attributes that are added
to every user entry.
A value is either a fixed string or a template containing one or more
.BI { placeholder }
sequences.
.PP
The following placeholders are recognised:
.PP
.TS
l l.
\fBPlaceholder\fR	\fBValue\fR
{uid}	Username
{cn}	Common name (derived from GECOS)
{sn}	Surname (last word of cn)
{uidNumber}	Numeric UID
{gidNumber}	Numeric GID
{homeDirectory}	Home directory path
{shell}	Login shell
{gecos}	Raw GECOS field
.TE
.PP
An unknown placeholder such as
.B {email}
is a fatal error at startup.
.PP
Attributes defined in
.B [user_attributes]
may replace built-in attributes such as
.B loginShell
or
.BR cn .
The four core identity attributes
.BR objectClass ,
.BR uid ,
.BR uidNumber ,
and
.B gidNumber
are protected: any attempt to override them produces a warning and is
silently ignored.
.PP
The
.B [user_overrides]
section allows per-user attribute values that take precedence over the
general
.B [user_attributes]
rules.
Each sub-table is keyed by username:
.PP
.RS
.nf
[user_overrides.alice]
mail = "alice@external.com"
.fi
.RE
.PP
Values in
.B [user_overrides]
are fixed strings; template placeholders are not expanded.
.
.SH BASE DN DERIVATION
When
.B base_dn
is not set in the configuration file,
.B pwldapd
derives the base DN from the system hostname:
.IP 1. 4
Call
.BR gethostname (2)
to obtain the local hostname.
.IP 2. 4
If the hostname contains at least one dot and the domain portion is not
.B local
or
.BR localdomain ,
convert the full hostname to a base DN by splitting on dots and
prepending each component with
.BR dc= .
For example,
.B server.example.com
becomes
.BR dc=server,dc=example,dc=com .
.IP 3. 4
If the hostname is unqualified (no dot), attempt a DNS canonical-name
lookup via
.BR getaddrinfo (3)
with
.B AI_CANONNAME
and repeat step\ 2 with the returned FQDN.
.PP
If the base DN cannot be determined,
.B pwldapd
exits with an error and
.B base_dn
must be set explicitly in the configuration file.
.
.SH IPv6
IPv6 addresses must be enclosed in square brackets in
.B listen
and
.BR tls_listen :
.PP
.RS
.nf
listen     = ["[::1]:389"]
tls_listen = ["[::]:636"]
.fi
.RE
.PP
If a port is omitted from a
.B listen
address,
.B :389
is appended automatically; for
.BR tls_listen ,
.B :636
is used.
.
.SH TLS (LDAPS)
.B pwldapd
supports TLS via the LDAPS convention (a separate port, typically 636,
where TLS is negotiated immediately upon connection).
StartTLS is not supported.
.PP
To enable TLS, set
.BR tls_cert ,
.BR tls_key ,
and one or more
.B tls_listen
addresses in the configuration file:
.PP
.RS
.nf
tls_listen = ["[::]:636"]
tls_cert   = "/etc/ssl/certs/ldap.pem"
tls_key    = "/etc/ssl/private/ldap.key"
.fi
.RE
.PP
Plain and TLS listeners can coexist:
.PP
.RS
.nf
listen     = ["127.0.0.1:389"]
tls_listen = ["[::]:636"]
tls_cert   = "/etc/ssl/certs/ldap.pem"
tls_key    = "/etc/ssl/private/ldap.key"
.fi
.RE
.
.SH UNIX DOMAIN SOCKETS
.B pwldapd
can accept connections over Unix domain sockets in addition to, or instead
of, TCP/IP.
This is useful for local clients that do not require network access.
.PP
Set
.B unix_listen
in the configuration file to a list of socket paths:
.PP
.RS
.nf
unix_listen = ["/run/pwldapd/ldap.sock"]
.fi
.RE
.PP
Multiple paths are supported.
Plain TCP, TLS, and Unix listeners can all run simultaneously.
.PP
If a socket file already exists at the given path when the daemon starts
(for example, left behind by a previous run), it is removed and recreated
automatically.
.PP
Clients connect using the
.B ldapi://
URI scheme.
The path is encoded as a URL, with
.B /
characters replaced by
.BR %2F :
.PP
.RS
.nf
ldapsearch \-H ldapi:///run/pwldapd/ldap.sock \-x \-b dc=example,dc=com
.fi
.RE
.
.SH BIND REQUIREMENT
By default any client\(emincluding unauthenticated anonymous clients\(emmay
perform search requests.
Setting
.B require_bind
to a list of account names restricts this: a client must successfully bind
as one of the named accounts before any search is permitted.
.PP
.RS
.nf
require_bind = ["svcaccount"]
.fi
.RE
.PP
This is intended for service accounts that authenticate themselves to the
server before retrieving directory data.
.PP
When
.B require_bind
is set:
.IP \(bu 4
An anonymous bind succeeds, but subsequent searches return result code 50
.RB ( INSUFFICIENT_ACCESS_RIGHTS ).
.IP \(bu 4
A bind as an account not in the list fails with
.B INVALID_CREDENTIALS
(rejected by PAM); searches remain blocked.
.IP \(bu 4
A bind as a listed account succeeds; searches are permitted for the
remainder of that connection.
.IP \(bu 4
Re-binding anonymously, or a failed bind, clears the authenticated identity;
searches are blocked again until a new successful bind.
.PP
When
.B require_bind
is empty (the default) all clients may search without binding.
.
.SH PAM CONFIGURATION
.B pwldapd
authenticates bind requests via PAM using the service name
.BR pwldapd .
The file
.B /etc/pam.d/pwldapd
must exist before any authenticated bind is attempted; without it PAM
falls back to
.BR /etc/pam.d/other ,
which on most systems denies all access.
.PP
A minimal configuration delegating to the standard system auth stack:
.PP
.RS
.nf
auth     required   pam_unix.so
account  required   pam_unix.so
.fi
.RE
.PP
On systems that use the include-based layout:
.PP
.RS
.nf
@include common-auth
@include common-account
.fi
.RE
.PP
Using a dedicated PAM service allows LDAP-specific policies such as
per-service failure delays, audit logging, or restricting which accounts
may bind via LDAP.
.
.SH GECOS PARSING
The GECOS field is interpreted as up to five comma-separated values in the
traditional BSD format:
.PP
.RS
.I "Full Name,Room Number,Work Phone,Home Phone,Other"
.RE
.PP
The full name becomes the
.BR cn ,
.BR sn ,
and (when two or more words are present)
.B givenName
attributes.
.BR roomNumber ,
.BR telephoneNumber ,
and
.B homePhone
are set from fields 1, 2, and 3 respectively when non-empty.
The fifth field has no standard LDAP mapping and is ignored.
.
.SH LISTENING ON PORT 389
Port 389 requires elevated privileges.
When installed from the Debian package the systemd unit runs
.B pwldapd
as the unprivileged
.B pwldapd
system user and grants
.B CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE
via
.BR AmbientCapabilities ,
so no additional configuration is needed.
.PP
When running outside of the package, the recommended approach is to grant
the binary the capability directly rather than running as root:
.PP
.RS
.nf
sudo setcap cap_net_bind_service=ep /usr/local/sbin/pwldapd
.fi
.RE
.PP
Alternatively, configure a firewall redirect from a high port:
.PP
.RS
.nf
iptables \-t nat \-A PREROUTING \-p tcp \-\-dport 389 \e
    \-j REDIRECT \-\-to\-port 3389
.fi
.RE
.PP
Or use a service manager that provides socket activation.
.
.SH LOGGING
Log verbosity is controlled by the
.B log_level
configuration key or the
.B RUST_LOG
environment variable.
The default level is
.BR info ,
which logs listener startup, each new connection, and all bind outcomes.
.PP
To set the log level in the configuration file:
.PP
.RS
.nf
log_level = "debug"
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B RUST_LOG
takes precedence over
.BR log_level .
Both accept the full tracing filter syntax; for example,
.B pwldapd=debug
enables debug logging for
.B pwldapd
only, while
.B debug
enables it for all crates.
.
.SH LIMITATIONS
.B pwldapd
is intentionally a read-only LDAP front-end.
The following features are not supported:
.IP \(bu 4
Write operations (Add, Delete, Modify, ModifyDN).
.IP \(bu 4
SASL authentication.
.IP \(bu 4
StartTLS (use a dedicated LDAPS port instead).
.IP \(bu 4
Referrals or server-side sorting.
.IP \(bu 4
Persistent searches or change notifications.
.IP \(bu 4
Server-enforced size limits or time limits (client-requested values are
accepted on the wire but ignored).
.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B RUST_LOG
Controls log verbosity; overrides
.B log_level
in the configuration file.
See
.BR LOGGING .
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /etc/pam.d/pwldapd
PAM service configuration for bind authentication.
Must be created before starting the daemon.
.TP
.B /etc/pwldapd.toml
Default TOML configuration file.
Loaded automatically if present when
.B \-\-config
is not specified.
.
.SH EXAMPLES
Serve local users on the loopback with default settings:
.PP
.RS
.nf
pwldapd
.fi
.RE
.PP
Load all settings from a configuration file:
.PP
.RS
.nf
pwldapd \-\-config /etc/pwldapd.toml
.fi
.RE
.PP
Typical
.B /etc/pwldapd.toml
serving on all interfaces with TLS:
.PP
.RS
.nf
listen     = ["[::]:389"]
tls_listen = ["[::]:636"]
base_dn    = "dc=corp,dc=example,dc=com"
uid_ranges = ["2000\-9999"]
tls_cert   = "/etc/ssl/certs/ldap.pem"
tls_key    = "/etc/ssl/private/ldap.key"
.fi
.RE
.PP
Serve only on a Unix domain socket (no TCP):
.PP
.RS
.nf
listen      = []
unix_listen = ["/run/pwldapd/ldap.sock"]
base_dn     = "dc=corp,dc=example,dc=com"
.fi
.RE
.PP
Point an NSS/LDAP client at a running TCP instance:
.PP
.RS
.nf
uri     ldap://127.0.0.1/
base    dc=host,dc=example,dc=com
.fi
.RE
.PP
Or, when using a Unix domain socket:
.PP
.RS
.nf
uri     ldapi:///run/pwldapd/ldap.sock
base    dc=host,dc=example,dc=com
.fi
.RE
(Replace the base DN with whatever
.B pwldapd
logs at startup.)
.
